ncient Roman ideas and controversies about the value of variety have had a significant afterlife up to our own time, Fitzgerald reveals how modern understandings of diversity and choice derive from what is ultimately an ancient concept.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aLatin literaturexHistory and criticism. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh  avariety, diversity, multiplicity, latin, literature, nature, rhetoric, creativity, pleasure, aesthetics, empire, lyric, elegy, satire, values, social change, nonfiction, history, philosophy, choice, pliny the younger, horace, lucretius, genre, listing, catalogues, whitman, ginsberg, subjectivity, varius, varietas, various, linguistics, language, conflict, difference, agency.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311071098440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226299525423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226299525/original  a978-3-11-071098-4  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles